{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:51:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:51:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"973"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/973"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.59,0.01,0.02,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/973"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36623"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with lower abdominal pain associated with nausea and vomiting. She has a medical history of polycystic ovary syndrome and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was 10 weeks ago and she reports vaginal bleeding today associated with her pain. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The abdomen is soft and there is no guarding though she is tender in the suprapubic region. On speculum examination, the cervical os is open but no products of conception are visible. A bedside transabdominal ultrasound demonstrates an intra-uterine pregnancy, fetal heartbeat visible, and no other visible masses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe urinalysis is negative. Urinary beta-hCG is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subchorionic haematoma","Inevitable miscarriage","Vasa praevia","Antepartum haemorrhage","Threatened miscarriage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with a miscarriage at 10 weeks gestation. The key finding in this case is the open cervical os on speculum examination, which, combined with vaginal bleeding, strongly suggests an \u003Cstrong\u003Einevitable miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn inevitable miscarriage refers to the presence of an open internal os with bleeding and/or pain. Products of conception are not yet expelled but inevitably will be. Often, but not always, products are present in the cervix at the time of examination. In this case, while no products are visible, the open os indicates that the miscarriage process has begun and cannot be stopped.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe term \u003Cstrong\u003Ethreatened miscarriage\u003C/strong\u003E applies to a pregnant woman who presents with vaginal bleeding bleeding but has a closed cervix and an otherwise viable pregnancy. In this case, the open cervical os rules out a threatened miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esubchorionic haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a collection of blood between the chorion and the uterine wall. It typically presents in the first trimester, though can present up to 20 weeks, and is thought to result from partial detachment of the chorionic membranes from the uterine wall. While it can present with vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy, the cervical os should remain closed. These are usually seen on ultrasound. For some patients, ultrasound is the only way a subchorionic haematoma is identified as they are otherwise asymptomatic. Subchorionic haematomas are often associated with threatened miscarriage and can increase the risk of pregnancy loss, especially if they are large or occur early in pregnancy. Management typically involves close monitoring and pelvic rest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasa praevia\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition in which fetal blood vessels run through the membranes covering the internal os of the cervix. It is a rare condition that typically presents with painless bleeding in the second or third trimester, not at 10 weeks gestation. Vasa praevia is associated with a high risk of fetal mortality if not diagnosed antenatally. It is often diagnosed during routine ultrasound screening in high-risk pregnancies and management usually involves planned caesarean section before the onset of labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntepartum haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E refers to bleeding from the genital tract after 20 weeks of gestation but before the onset of labour. This patient is only at 10 weeks gestation, so this diagnosis does not apply. Important causes to consider include placenta praevia, placental abruption and uterine rupture. Antepartum haemorrhage is classified as minor, major or massive and can threaten the life of both mother and fetus. Immediate management includes left lateral positioning, establishing intravenous access and providing fluid resuscitation, assessment of maternal and fetal wellbing and considering blood transfusion and potential emergency delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe approach to assessing vaginal bleeding in pregnancy varies according to gestational age and clinical presentation. In early pregnancy (less than 20 weeks), the differential diagnoses include miscarriage, ectopic pregnancy, implantation bleeding, bleeding cervical polyps and subchorionic haematoma. Key steps in assessment include taking a thorough antenatal history, confirming gestational age, assessing the state of the cervix and confirming the location and viability of the pregnancy with ultrasound. In later pregnancy, the assessment focuses more on fetal wellbeing, placental location, and assessing the need for early delivery. As gestation progresses beyond 20 weeks, the causes of vaginal bleeding are more likely to be due to placental issues (such as placenta praevia or abruption), cervical pathology (like cervical ectropion or polyps), uterine rupture, vasa praevia, or the onset of labour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An open internal os in the presence of vaginal bleeding suggests an inevitable miscarriage.","The approach to vaginal bleeding in pregnancy varies depending on gestational age and clinical presentation."],"references":["Inevitable miscarriage.\u00a0https://radiopaedia.org/articles/inevitable-miscarriage. Accessed 13/7/2020.","The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. PROMPT Course Manual Australian and New Zealand Edition. Cambridge University Press; 2020.","SA Health. South Australian Perinatal Practice Guidelines: Bleeding in Early Pregnancy [Internet].  Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37/Bleeding+in+Early+Pregnancy_PPG_v1_3.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37-p4bu9Q.","Sapra KJ, Joseph KS, Galea S, et al. Signs and Symptoms of Early Pregnancy Loss. Reprod Sci 2017; 24:502"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36623"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"973"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36623"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-24T04:47:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T14:36:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"973"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51334"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":